The Battle of the Bulge took place from mid-December 1944 to mid-January 1945. It was an attempt by the Germans to split the Allied forces in the Western Front in half, and then surround them. This could force the Allies to negotiate a cease-fire. The secrecy of this operation on the part of the Germans contributed to its initial success. They caught the Allies completely by surprise, pushing the front line back and creating the “bulge” that gives the battle its most recognized Unit. It took place only a few months after the Allied invasion of Normandy.
	I downloaded eleven situation maps for different days of the battle from the Library of Congress, and then was able to digitize them using MICRODEM and register them to be displayed in Google Earth. I then marked all of the unit locations and created a moving timeline where the viewer can see the locations for the different days, and see how the front line moved drastically over the month long period of time that became such a pivotal battle in World War II.
